<h1 class="hero-h">2026 fractional CMO &amp; CRO <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">pricing benchmark.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">An observational pricing benchmark for fractional CMO, CRO, CFO, and COO engagements at B2B mid-market companies in May 2026. Built from Treetop's engagement observations, public job posts, and competitor pricing visibility. Citable numbers labeled by confidence level.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">About this benchmark</span><h2 class="h2">Methodology and limits</h2><p class="body"><strong>What this is:</strong> An observational pricing benchmark for fractional CMO, CRO, CFO, and COO engagements at B2B mid-market companies ($3M-$50M ARR). Synthesized from Treetop's engagement work, conversations with peer firms, public job postings, and competitor pricing visibility, May 2026.</p><p class="body"><strong>What this isn't:</strong> A formal survey. The fractional executive market is opaque by nature — rates vary by operator profile, engagement scope, and negotiation. Use these numbers as a starting point for budgeting and benchmarking, not as the floor or ceiling for any specific engagement.</p><div class="callout"><p>Permission to cite: Yes, with attribution to Treetop Growth Strategy and a link to this page. Numbers are refreshed quarterly.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Fractional CMO pricing — May 2026</span><h2 class="h2">By company size</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Company stage</th><th>Median monthly fee</th><th>Typical range</th><th>Typical time commitment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>$3M-$10M ARR</td><td>\$10,000</td><td>\$8K-\$15K</td><td>1 day/week</td></tr><tr><td>$10M-$25M ARR</td><td>\$15,000</td><td>\$12K-\$22K</td><td>1-2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$25M-$50M ARR</td><td>\$22,000</td><td>\$18K-\$30K</td><td>2-3 days/week</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="body"><strong>Profile premium:</strong> operators with deep vertical expertise (e.g., fintech, healthtech, devtools) typically command 10-25% premiums over generalist fractionals at the same time commitment.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Fractional CRO pricing — May 2026</span><h2 class="h2">By company size</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Company stage</th><th>Median monthly fee</th><th>Typical range</th><th>Typical time commitment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>$3M-$10M ARR</td><td>\$12,000</td><td>\$10K-\$18K</td><td>1 day/week</td></tr><tr><td>$10M-$25M ARR</td><td>\$18,000</td><td>\$15K-\$25K</td><td>1-2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$25M-$50M ARR</td><td>\$25,000</td><td>\$20K-\$35K</td><td>2-3 days/week</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="body">Fractional CRO rates run ~15-20% higher than fractional CMO at the same company stage, reflecting cross-functional scope (sales + CS + RevOps) and higher accountability for revenue numbers.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Fractional CFO pricing — May 2026</span><h2 class="h2">By company size</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Company stage</th><th>Median monthly fee</th><th>Typical range</th><th>Typical time commitment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>$3M-$10M ARR</td><td>\$8,000</td><td>\$6K-\$12K</td><td>1-2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$10M-$25M ARR</td><td>\$12,000</td><td>\$9K-\$18K</td><td>2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$25M-$50M ARR</td><td>\$16,000</td><td>\$13K-\$22K</td><td>2-3 days/week</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Fractional COO / Chief of Staff pricing</span><h2 class="h2">By company size</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Company stage</th><th>Median monthly fee</th><th>Typical range</th><th>Typical time commitment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>$3M-$10M ARR</td><td>\$9,000</td><td>\$7K-\$14K</td><td>1-2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$10M-$25M ARR</td><td>\$14,000</td><td>\$11K-\$20K</td><td>2 days/week</td></tr><tr><td>$25M-$50M ARR</td><td>\$18,000</td><td>\$15K-\$25K</td><td>2-3 days/week</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What's typically included</span><h2 class="h2">Scope by tier</h2><h3 class="h3">At \$8K-\$12K/month</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Weekly working session with founder/CEO</li><li>Direction-setting and prioritization</li><li>Documented quarterly roadmap</li><li>Light executional support; mostly direction</li><li>Async check-ins between sessions</li></ul><h3 class="h3">At \$12K-\$20K/month</h3><ul class="ul"><li>All of the above, plus:</li><li>Direct work on highest-leverage initiatives</li><li>Team management (1-2 direct reports possible)</li><li>Vendor management</li><li>Quarterly business reviews owned by fractional</li></ul><h3 class="h3">At \$20K+/month</h3><ul class="ul"><li>All of the above, plus:</li><li>Full P&amp;L responsibility for the function</li><li>Team management of 3-5 reports</li><li>Board reporting</li><li>Hiring leadership for the function (often including hiring the eventual full-time replacement)</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Engagement structure norms</span><h2 class="h2">What's standard in 2026</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Minimum commitment:</strong> 6 months. Most engagements run 12-18 months.</li><li><strong>Notice period:</strong> 30 days standard. 60 days for senior CRO/CMO with team management responsibility.</li><li><strong>Equity:</strong> uncommon at \$8K-\$15K/month; sometimes added at \$15K+/month, typically 0.1-0.5% over 2-year vest.</li><li><strong>Performance bonus:</strong> uncommon for fractional CMOs; more common for fractional CROs tied to revenue metrics.</li><li><strong>Travel/expenses:</strong> typically reimbursed; not built into the monthly fee.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Geographic variations</span><h2 class="h2">Where rates differ</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Bay Area / NYC:</strong> typically 10-20% above the medians shown, reflecting talent cost.</li><li><strong>Boston / Seattle / LA:</strong> rough parity with the medians shown.</li><li><strong>Austin / Denver / Chicago / Atlanta:</strong> rough parity with medians; some operators discount 5-15% from coastal-market rates.</li><li><strong>Remote / smaller markets:</strong> typically 5-15% below medians, though top-tier operators command coastal rates regardless of location.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What's driving 2026 pricing</span><h2 class="h2">Recent trends</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Supply has grown faster than demand.</strong> Tech-sector talent disruption has put more senior operators into fractional roles. Rates have plateaued or softened modestly at the generalist tier.</li><li><strong>Vertical specialists hold pricing.</strong> Fintech, healthtech, devtools, B2B SaaS specialists with named successful engagements command stable or rising rates.</li><li><strong>AI-augmented fractional work compounds value per hour.</strong> Some fractional executives now do meaningfully more work per day than 2-3 years ago, putting modest upward pressure on per-day rates from top performers.</li><li><strong>'Builder' profile premiums rising.</strong> Buyers increasingly distinguish execution-capable fractionals from strategy-only fractionals, with willingness to pay 10-20% premiums for the former.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">How to use these numbers</span><h2 class="h2">For buyers and operators</h2><h3 class="h3">If you're a buyer</h3><p class="body">Use these as anchor points for negotiation. Don't expect to hire well-below-median; don't pay well-above-median without specific justification (vertical expertise, recent track record, network access). Always negotiate scope clarity before negotiating rate.</p><h3 class="h3">If you're a fractional operator</h3><p class="body">If your rates are well below median, you're either early-stage in fractional work or underselling. If above median, you should be able to articulate the specific edge — don't expect buyers to pay 30%+ premium without proof.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Methodology</span><h2 class="h2">Sources</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Treetop's own engagement portfolio and pipeline conversations.</li><li>Direct conversations with ~15 peer fractional consultancies and individual operators.</li><li>Public LinkedIn job postings for fractional roles.</li><li>Competitor pricing pages (where publicly listed).</li><li>Buyer conversations during prospect calls.</li><li>Sample skews toward B2B SaaS and services; light coverage of consumer brands.</li><li>Last refresh: May 2026. Updated quarterly.</li></ul></div></section>

